# TriageProf Change Log

## 2026-03-01 02:15:00
- **Objective**: Enhanced WebSocket Real-time Monitoring with Live Data Streaming
- **Rationale**: Enable continuous performance monitoring with automatic updates and comprehensive statistics
- **Impact**: WebSocket server, web viewer, CLI interface, core pipeline
- **Changes**:
  - Added `StartAutoRefresh()` method to WebSocket server for periodic data updates
  - Enhanced `BroadcastData()` with comprehensive statistics including client count and severity breakdown
  - Added `UpdateData()` method for dynamic data updates without restarting server
  - Implemented `GetClientCount()` for monitoring connected clients
  - Enhanced WebSocket stats display in web viewer with animated severity breakdown
  - Added real-time update notifications with slide-in animations
  - Updated CLI with `--auto-refresh` flag for configurable update intervals (2-60 seconds)
  - Added comprehensive WebSocket server unit tests
  - Enhanced WebSocket protocol with detailed performance metrics
  - Fixed mutex deadlock issues in data update operations
  - Improved error handling and graceful degradation
- **Testing**: Unit tests for WebSocket server functionality, integration testing with CLI, manual WebSocket connection testing
- **Result**: Production-ready real-time monitoring with live data streaming, enhanced UI, comprehensive statistics, and robust error handling

## 2026-03-01 21:30: WebSocket Real-time Monitoring Implementation
- **Objective**: Implement WebSocket-based real-time data streaming for live performance monitoring
- **Rationale**: Enable continuous, low-latency monitoring of running applications without manual file uploads or refresh operations, providing true real-time performance analysis capabilities for production environments
- **Impact**: Core architecture, web viewer functionality, real-time monitoring capabilities, production monitoring workflows, API surface
- **Changes**:
  - Created new `internal/webserver` package with WebSocket server implementation using gorilla/websocket
  - Implemented WebSocketServer struct with client management, data broadcasting, and health monitoring
  - Added WebSocket connection handlers for real-time data streaming with automatic client registration
  - Enhanced web viewer JavaScript with WebSocket client functionality and connection management
  - Added WebSocket controls to HTML UI with connection status indicators and URL configuration
  - Extended CSS with WebSocket-specific styles for connection states and controls
  - Updated core Pipeline struct to support WebSocket server configuration and management
  - Added new `websocket` CLI command for starting real-time monitoring servers
  - Implemented health check endpoint for monitoring server status and connected clients
  - Added data broadcasting functionality to push updates to all connected clients
  - Enhanced error handling and graceful shutdown for WebSocket operations
- **Testing**: Unit testing of WebSocket server functionality; manual testing of connection lifecycle; verification of data streaming; health endpoint validation; integration testing with web viewer; stress testing with multiple concurrent clients
- **Result**: TriageProf now supports true real-time performance monitoring via WebSocket protocol, enabling production-grade continuous analysis without manual intervention. The WebSocket server provides low-latency data streaming, automatic client management, and robust error handling. Users can now monitor running applications in real-time, receive instant performance updates, and integrate TriageProf into production monitoring dashboards. The implementation maintains backward compatibility while adding powerful new capabilities for live performance analysis.
